    <div class="grid-12 body-text">
        <p class="cols-left-half">
            Construction was a serious challenge. I quickly realized that I'd made my life difficult by choosing to build a large piece of furniture (versus, say, a stool). Large size + inexperience + perfectionism were a dangerous combination. I'd been careful to choose good boards, but they still needed to be squared up where edges met, at a minimum. Without an electric planer or jointer, this was done by hand, using a <a href="https://www.stanleytools.com/products/hand-tools/cutting-tools/planes/no-62-sweetheart-low-angle-jack-plane/12-137">Stanley jack plane</a>, and some mediocre clamping arragements on my (too small) workbench.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div>
        <img src="img/desk-cauls.png" data-lightbox></img>
        <p class="caption small-text">Making <a href="https://www.finewoodworking.com/2011/03/08/clamping-cauls-the-secret-to-great-glue-ups">cauls</a> to help align the boards of the top when they are glued up.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="grid-12 body-text">
        <p class="cols-left-half">
            In some cases, tools needed to be made from scratch before work could progress. A workbench was the first thing that was built. I needed a surface on which I could do everything from sawing to planing, and that would fit within the space constraints of our apartment's patio and storage locker. After much research I went with a low <a href="https://blog.lostartpress.com/2018/02/22/ingenious-mechanicks-chapter-by-chapter/">roman workbench</a>. 
        </p>
